'''Sir D'Arcy Power''', [[Knight Commander of the Order of the British Empire|KBE]], [[Fellow of the Royal College of Surgeons|FRCS]], [[Fellow of the Society of Antiquaries of London|FSA]] (11 November 1855 in [[Pimlico]], London - 18 May 1941) was a British [[surgeon]], medical historian, and contributor of some 200 articles on famous surgeons and other related figures to the ''[[Dictionary of National Biography]]''.<ref name="RSoc">{{cite journal|journal=Proceedings of the [[Royal Society of Medicine]]|year=1963|volume=56(Suppl 1)|pages=24–25|title=Sir D'Arcy Power| first=W. R.|last=LeFanu|accessdate = 2 May 2010|pmc=1896749|pmid=14044493}}</ref>

==Medical career==
The eldest son of a six boys and five girls, D'Arcy was born on 11 November 1855 at 3 Grosvenor Terrace, Pimlico, in London, the son of Henry Power, himself a surgeon.<ref name="odnb">{{Cite web|first=Harold|last=Ellis|title=Power, Sir D'Arcy (1855–1941)|work=Oxford Dictionary of National Biography|publisher=Oxford University Press|month=September|year=2004 (onlined edition October 2006)| url=http://www.oxforddnb.com/view/article/35593|accessdate=2 May 2010}}</ref> He was educated at [[Merchant Taylors' School, Northwood]] and entered [[New College, Oxford]], before transferring to [[Exeter College, Oxford|Exeter College]].<ref name="odnb"/> Though he wanted to be a [[physiologist]], he ended up following his father into becoming a surgeon (at [[St. Bartholomew's Hospital]]).<ref name="RSoc" /> In this vein, he because a [[Fellow of the Royal College of Surgeons]] in 1883, serving as a member of its council from 1912 to 1928, and being its vice-president for the years 1921 and 1922.<ref name="odnb"/><ref>{{London Gazette|issue=28619|startpage=4429|date=18 June 1912|accessdate=4 May 2010}}</ref> He gave the [[Royal College of Surgeons of England#Bradshaw Lecture|Bradshaw Lecture]] for 1918, the [[Vicary lecture]] for 1920, and delivered the [[Hunterian oration]] in 1925.<ref name="odnb"/> He was variously also the [[Mitchell Banks]] Memorial Lecturer in 1933; a member of the executive committee of the [[Imperial Cancer Research Fund]]; President of the [[Medical Society of London]]; President of the [http://www.harveiansocietyoflondon.com Harveian Society of London] and President of the Section of the History of Medicine at the [[Royal Society of Medicine]], 1926 to 1928.<ref>{{Cite web|title=Power, Sir D’Arcy|work=Who Was Who|publisher=A & C Black|edition=online|publisher=Oxford University Press|date=December 2007|url=http://www.ukwhoswho.com/view/article/oupww/whowaswho/U230603|accessdate=2 May 2010}}</ref> Power also both taught and examined in medicine and wrote textbooks and articles for a number of medical journals.<ref name="RSoc" />

===Army service===
Commissioned as a surgeon in the [[Volunteer Medical Staff Corps]] on 25 April 1888,<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=25810|startpage=2330|date=24 April 1888|accessdate=4 May 2010}}</ref> Power was given the rank of [[major (United Kingdom)|major]] in the [[Royal Army Medical Corps]] when its [[Territorial Force]] section was created on 31 July 1908, and was attached to [[1st London General Hospital]].<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=28181|startpage=7020|date=29 September 1908|accessdate=4 May 2010}}</ref> He was mobilised with the outbreak of the [[First World War]] in August 1914, and promoted [[Lieutenant Colonel (United Kingdom)|lieutenant-colonel]] on 22 August.<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=28876|startpage=6606|date=29 September 1908|accessdate=4 May 2010}}</ref> Until 1916 he was based at the officers' hospital at [[Fishmongers' Hall]], and then rejoined the main body of 1st London General Hospital, serving until demobilisation in 1920,<ref name="odnb"/> Power was appointed [[Knight Commander of the Order of the British Empire]] in recognition of his service in military hospitals during the First World War in the 1919 [[King's Birthday Honours]].<ref name="RSoc" /><ref>{{London Gazette|issue=31395|startpage=7425|endpage=7426|date=6 June 1919|accessdate=4 May 2010}}</ref>  He retired from the army on 30 September 1921.<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=32786|startpage=306|date=12 January 1923|accessdate=4 May 2010}}</ref>

==Personal life==
He married Eleanor Fosbroke in 1883; she predeceased him in 1923. They had two sons and a daughter.<ref name="odnb"/>  The older son, also called [[D'Arcy Power (Royal Air Force officer)|D'Arcy Power]], followed his father into part-time service in the RAMC in 1911,<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=28527|startpage=6456|date=1 September 1911|accessdate=4 May 2010}}</ref> and during the First World War became a captain and won the [[Military Cross]].<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=29608|supp=yes|startpage=5570|endpage=5576|date=2 June 1916|accessdate=4 May 2010}}</ref>  He transferred to the Medical Branch of the [[Royal Air Force]] on the formation of the new service on 1 April 1918<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=31112|startpage=369|date=7 January 1919|accessdate=4 May 2010}}</ref>—taking a permanent commission as a [[flight lieutenant]] in 1920<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=31978|startpage=7458|date=13 July 1920|accessdate=4 May 2010}}</ref>—and ultimately reaching the rank of acting [[air vice marshal]] by 1945 when he was appointed [[Commander of the Order of the British Empire]].<ref name="odnb"/><ref>{{London Gazette|issue=37119|supp=yes|startpage=2947|date=8 June 1945|accessdate=4 May 2010}}</ref> The younger son, George Henry Fosbroke Power, died at the [[Second Battle of Ypres]] in 1915 when he was serving as a [[First Lieutenant|lieutenant]] in 6th Battalion, [[Middlesex Regiment]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cwgc.org/search/casualty_details.aspx?casualty=1624754|title=Casualty Details—Power, George Henry Fosbroke|publisher=[[Commonwealth War Graves Commission|accessdate=4 May 2010]]}}</ref> Power's daughter died young of [[whooping cough]].<ref name="odnb"/> Power, who was presented on his 75th birthday with a bibliography listing 609 of his "selected writings" by a special committee of the [[Osler Club]], was also a [[Fellow of the Society of Antiquaries of London]] (where he was, for some time, a member of the council) and President of the [[Bibliographical Society]] from 1926 to 1928.<ref name="RSoc" /> After his home was damaged in an air raid in 1940, Power moved in with his son at 53 Murray Road, [[Northwood, Middlesex]], where he died on 18 May 1941.<ref name="odnb"/>

== Notable works ==
Power's more notable standalone works included:<ref name="odnb"/>
* ''William Harvey'' (1897) on the life of [[William Harvey]];
* ''Portraits of Dr William Harvey'' (1913);
* ''Foundations of Medical History'' (1931);
* ''A Short History of Surgery'' (1933);
* ''Mirror for Surgeons'', an anthology (1939).

